DailyBugle

Target IP: 10.10.250.199
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan shows there are three TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above. There are SSH, HTTP, and MySQL applications on the target machine.


Doing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above. Now I have more information about the target machine. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to port 80 displays the webpage above. The target machine seems to be running Joomla CMS.


Using the command droopescan scan joomla -u http://10.10.250.199, I obtained the useful scan result above against the Joomla CMS. This scan gives more information about the Joomla CMS.


Browsing to http://10.10.250.199/administrator/manifests/files/joomla.xml shows the config file above. The target machine seems to be running Joomla CMS 3.7.0, as shown above.


And searching for exploits for Joomla 3.7.0 shows it is vulnerable to SQL injection. This vulnerability has the CVE id of CVE-2017-8917. I found the exploit above at GitHub for this application version. I downloaded a copy of this exploit on my machine. I enumerated the machine further to find any useful directories, files, etc, but I had no luck. Time to test my luck with the exploit.

Exploitation


I ran the exploit against the target machine using the command python3 exp.py http://10.10.250.199 and obtained the result above. The exploit successfully managed to extract data from the table fb9j5_users. There exists one user called jonah with the email jonah@tryhackme.com and password hash of $2y$10$0veO/JSFh4389Lluc4Xya.dfy2MF.bZhz0jVMw.V.d3p12kBtZutm. Maybe I can crack this user's password hash to gain access to the web application as the user jonah?


I copied the password hash of the user jonah to a text file called hash, as shown above.


Using john, I managed to crack the password hash and obtain the password spiderman123 as shown above. Now I have the credentials jonah:spiderman123 for the web application. I can run this credentials against the administrator panel I found from the droopescan.


I browsed to the http://10.10.250.199/administrator webpage to login.


And bingo! Now I have access to the administrator panel of the Joomla CMS, as shown above. Right away, I notice the Templates is enabled. Meaning, I can upload my own version of malicious PHP reverse shell and access it to gain a foothold on the target machine.


I changed the error.php file of template Beez3 with PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell as shown above. Then I started a listener on my machine at port 8443.


And bingo! I browsed to http://10.10.250.199/templates/beez3/error.php and obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443 as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as apache.

Privilege Escalation


The file configuration.php contains the username and password above.


From manual enumeration, I found one user called jjameson. However, I cannot access their files. But using su and the password nv5uz9r3ZEDzVjNu, I successfully switched to this user. I successfully elevated my privileges horizontally from apache to jjameson as shown above.


Running sudo -l shows the command /usr/bin/yum can be executed as the user root without password. Maybe I can use this to gain a root shell?


I obtained the commands above from GTFOBins to execute yum using sudo. As shown in the image above, it spawns a root shell by loading a custom plugin (a shell).
